          "rules": [
            {
              "id": "often-misused/authentication/3DD14DE38594C51AEAB9A46DF2EB085F",
              "shortDescription": { "text": "Often Misused: Authentication" },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "AuthenticationFilter determines login state solely by the presence of a cookie named \"user\". Cookies are client-controlled and unsigned, so an attacker can set user=anything to bypass authentication and access all non-whitelisted paths. Related flow: AuthenticationController.login() sets this cookie; MessageController reads it as the message author identity.",
                "markdown": "`AuthenticationFilter` decides login state **solely from the presence of a cookie named `user`**. Cookies are client-controlled and unsigned, so an attacker can simply send `Cookie: user=admin` to bypass authentication and reach every non-whitelisted path.\n\n**Exploit flow**\n\n1. `AuthenticationController.login()` sets the `user` cookie on success.\n2. `AuthenticationFilter.doFilter()` treats the mere presence of that cookie as proof of authentication.\n3. `MessageController` trusts the same cookie as the message author identity, enabling impersonation."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Stop trusting a client-side cookie as the authentication state; use a real server-side session instead:\n\n1. In AuthenticationController.login(), after verifying credentials, store the user server-side: request.getSession().setAttribute(\"user\", username).\n2. In AuthenticationFilter.doFilter(), derive loggedIn from session.getAttribute(\"user\") != null rather than cookie presence.\n3. Remove the client-visible user cookie entirely so it can no longer be forged.\n\nSee the OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet.",
                "markdown": "Stop trusting a client-side cookie as the authentication state; use a real server-side session instead:\n\n1. In `AuthenticationController.login()`, after verifying credentials, store the user server-side: `request.getSession().setAttribute(\"user\", username)`.\n2. In `AuthenticationFilter.doFilter()`, derive `loggedIn` from `session.getAttribute(\"user\") != null` rather than cookie presence.\n3. Remove the client-visible `user` cookie entirely so it can no longer be forged.\n\nSee the [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)."
              },
              "properties": {
                "kingdom": "API Abuse",
                "Type": "Often Misused",
                "SubType": "Authentication",
                "security-severity": "9.8",
                "Impact": 4.0,
                "Probability": 4.0
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "cross-site-scripting/persistent/CFE4E750668A04EB465124ADB05C2FD8",
              "shortDescription": { "text": "Cross-Site Scripting: Persistent" },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "User-supplied message body is stored via MessageDAO.post() (raw SQL INSERT, no sanitization) and later rendered unescaped in read.jsp through ${msg.body}. Attacker-controlled HTML and JavaScript persists in the database and executes in every viewer's browser session.",
                "markdown": "User-supplied message body is stored via `MessageDAO.post()` (raw SQL `INSERT`, no sanitization) and later rendered **unescaped** in `read.jsp` via `${msg.body}`. Any HTML or JavaScript an author submits is persisted and then executes in **every** viewer's browser.\n\nExploitation requires an authenticated account that can post a message, which lowers the likelihood somewhat, but a single stored payload then affects all readers."
              },
              "help": {
                "text": "Encode on output and sanitize on input:\n\n- In read.jsp, replace ${msg.body} with <c:out value=\"${msg.body}\"/> so the value is HTML-encoded. Add the JSTL core taglib if it is not already imported.\n- In MessageDAO.post(), sanitize incoming HTML with an allowlist library such as the OWASP Java HTML Sanitizer before persisting.",
                "markdown": "Encode on output and sanitize on input:\n\n- In `read.jsp`, replace `${msg.body}` with `<c:out value=\"${msg.body}\"/>` so the value is HTML-encoded. Add `<%@ taglib prefix=\"c\" uri=\"http://java.sun.com/jsp/jstl/core\" %>` if it is not already imported.\n- In `MessageDAO.post()`, sanitize incoming HTML with an allowlist library such as the [OWASP Java HTML Sanitizer](https://github.com/OWASP/java-html-sanitizer) before persisting."
              },
              "properties": {
                "kingdom": "Input Validation and Representation",
                "Type": "Cross-Site Scripting",
                "SubType": "Persistent",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "Impact": 4.0,
                "Probability": 2.0
              }
            }
          ]
        }
      },
